# Documentation Cleanup Rules

## Principle: Keep Only Critical Information

Documentation should contain only essential information that helps developers understand the app's architecture, unique features, and critical implementation details. Remove obvious, repetitive, or verbose content.

## What to Remove

### Obvious Installation Steps

- Standard `git clone` explanations
- Basic `npm install` instructions
- Common development server setup
- Generic prerequisite lists (Node.js, npm, etc.)

### Verbose Feature Lists

- Marketing-style bullet points with excessive detail
- Repetitive feature descriptions
- Over-explained benefits that are self-evident
- Multiple sections covering the same information

### Step-by-Step Tutorials

- Basic command explanations that are self-documenting
- Obvious workflow descriptions
- Generic troubleshooting sections
- Detailed examples for simple operations

### Redundant Sections

- Multiple sections explaining the same concept
- Repetitive configuration examples
- Duplicate information across different docs
- Over-detailed table comparisons for simple concepts

### Marketing Language

- Adjectives ("amazing", "powerful", "advanced", "modern", "beautiful", etc.)
- Excessive emoji usage for simple sections
- Promotional language about features
- Verbose explanations of obvious benefits

## What to Keep

### Critical Technical Information

- Unique architecture decisions (SSR optimizations, MathJax integration)
- Non-obvious configuration requirements
- Complex setup procedures that differ from standards
- Performance considerations and thresholds

### Essential API Information

- Environment variables with specific purposes
- Critical configuration options
- Non-standard build processes
- Integration-specific requirements

### Key Implementation Details

- Custom algorithms or business logic
- Third-party integration notes
- Performance monitoring thresholds
- Security considerations

### Troubleshooting (Selective)

- Common issues specific to this project
- Non-obvious error resolution
- Critical debugging information
- Project-specific gotchas

## Documentation Structure Guidelines

### README Files

- Lead with brief, factual description
- Focus on unique features, not standard tech stack benefits
- Include only essential setup commands
- Highlight critical configuration requirements
- End with minimal technical details

### Technical Documentation

- Start with overview of what makes this implementation unique
- Include only critical configuration options
- Focus on project-specific requirements
- Remove generic explanations of well-known tools

### API Documentation

- Include only non-standard usage patterns
- Document critical environment variables
- Explain complex integrations briefly
- Remove obvious parameter explanations

## Writing Style

### Be Concise

- Use direct, factual language
- Eliminate unnecessary words
- Combine related concepts
- Remove redundant explanations

### Focus on Value

- Each section should answer "Why is this different/important?"
- Remove content that doesn't help developers understand or implement
- Prioritize actionable information over descriptive content
- Include only critical examples

### Maintain Technical Accuracy

- Keep all technical details accurate
- Preserve critical code examples
- Maintain essential configuration information
- Don't remove important warnings or notes

